27:49.902 --> 27:57.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MATT FREI, INDEPENDENT
TELEVISION NEWS: Everything
you're about to see happened
over 48 hours

27:57.409 --> 27:58.510 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in July in Aleppo.

27:58.544 --> 28:10.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the streets outside, the
sound and fury
of war.

28:10.856 --> 28:12.891 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(SIREN WAILING)

28:12.925 --> 28:21.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The toll that day: 45 dead,
dozens wounded.

28:21.199 --> 28:33.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But inside: the reverential
concentration
of ant makeshift theater.

28:33.312 --> 28:37.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The woman on the operating table
is called
Maisa (ph).

28:37.082 --> 28:41.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She is nine months' pregnant and
she was caught
up in one of the bombings when
she was on

28:41.420 --> 28:45.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
her way to the hospital, by
foot, close to
labor.

28:45.223 --> 28:47.159 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Let me see.

28:47.192 --> 28:50.429 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Wipe it with a swab.

28:50.462 --> 28:53.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Examine her hand and see if
there is shrapnel.

28:53.298 --> 28:55.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There isn't anything.

28:55.200 --> 28:58.570 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Give me the scalpel.

28:58.604 --> 29:04.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREI: In explosion, she broke
her right arm
and leg, but what the doctors
are concerned

29:05.010 --> 29:10.582 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about most is the shrapnel in
her belly.

29:10.616 --> 29:15.754 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Did it kill her baby?

29:15.787 --> 29:19.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They want to perform an
emergency cesarean.

29:19.825 --> 29:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What you're witnessing is the
fight to save
one new life.

29:28.066 --> 29:36.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In a city that is more used to
dealing with
untimely deaths

29:36.108 --> 29:40.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the operating theater, the
fight for life
appears victorious.

29:40.979 --> 29:46.118 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But there seems to be a problem.

29:46.151 --> 29:49.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Is his heart
beating?

29:49.121 --> 29:50.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: No.

29:50.956 --> 29:53.825 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
No, I'm sorry.

29:53.859 --> 30:00.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
FREI: The doctors fight on.

30:00.899 --> 30:14.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're now in danger of losing
both child
and mother.

30:14.646 --> 30:24.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The struggle to save new life is
visceral,
instinctive, perhaps because
outside death

30:24.990 --> 30:30.262 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
comes so easily.

30:30.295 --> 30:43.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then the umbilical cord twitches
-- proof
of life.

30:43.108 --> 30:53.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: He's getting
a rosy color
now.

30:53.318 --> 30:59.324 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(BABY CRYING)

30:59.357 --> 31:11.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FREI: And the most elemental
sound of all.

31:11.336 --> 31:17.242 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(BABY CRYING)

31:17.275 --> 31:31.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FREI: More powerful for a brief
moment than
Aleppo's daily cry of death.

31:31.156 --> 31:35.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

31:35.227 --> 31:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: It's hard not tore
be moved by
images like that, but some
pictures capture

31:41.199 --> 31:43.535 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the world's attention more than
others.

31:43.568 --> 31:47.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We begin with an image that
emerged last night
from the frantic attempts to
rescue people

31:47.973 --> 31:51.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
caught in the aftermath of air
strikes.

31:51.510 --> 31:55.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And again, another warning: some
images in
this story may disturb some
viewers.

31:55.881 --> 31:57.048 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

31:57.082 --> 32:00.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Air strikes are
Aleppo's terrible
routine.

32:00.385 --> 32:03.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This one hit an apartment a
building in the
city's rebel-held area.

32:03.922 --> 32:08.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Amateur video captured the
frantic scramble
to save lives amid horror.

32:08.126 --> 32:12.297 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then, a boy, pulled from the
rubble, sits
in an ambulance.

32:12.330 --> 32:15.567 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's dazed, bloodied, covered in
dust.

32:15.600 --> 32:17.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He wipes his face.

32:17.302 --> 32:19.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
His name: Omran Daqneesh.

32:19.104 --> 32:20.205 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Age five.

32:20.238 --> 32:21.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He survived without major
injuries.

32:21.673 --> 32:24.176 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So did his parents and three
young siblings.

32:24.209 --> 32:30.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Almost immediately, his image
swept across
social media worldwide, making
Omran the latest

32:30.048 --> 32:33.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
symbol of heartbreak in the
now-five year
old conflict.

32:33.785 --> 32:35.787 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But do such images spark action?

32:35.821 --> 32:37.956 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
If so, when?

32:37.989 --> 32:39.524 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
And how?

32:39.558 --> 32:43.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, as the refugee crisis
swelled,
one photo came to embody the
tragedy.

32:43.962 --> 32:50.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A drowned, three-year-old Syrian
boy, pictured
lying face down on a Turkish
beach.

32:50.602 --> 32:56.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It galvanized European leaders
to review how
they take in refugees and
asylum-seekers.

32:56.741 --> 32:58.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Other instances had less impact.

32:58.143 --> 33:03.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In 2012, a documentary about
Ugandan war-lord
Joseph Kony went viral.

33:03.949 --> 33:09.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It detailed the brutal tactics
of his "Lord's
Resistance Army," and the
group's use of child

33:09.054 --> 33:10.755 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
soldiers.

33:10.789 --> 33:16.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With the hashtags "Kony 2012"
and "Stop Kony,"
it sparked global calls for his
arrest.

33:16.061 --> 33:20.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But four years later, Kony
reportedly remains
at large.

33:20.198 --> 33:26.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in April 2014, the Islamist
group Boko
Haram seized more than 270 girls
from their

33:26.404 --> 33:29.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
school in northeast Nigeria.

33:29.908 --> 33:34.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It led to the "Bring Back Our
Girls" campaign,
repeated and circulated by
prominent figures

33:35.013 --> 33:37.015 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
like first lady Michelle Obama.

33:37.048 --> 33:42.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this week, new video from
Boko Haram surfaced
showing dozens of the girls
still in captivity,

33:42.687 --> 33:44.522 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more than two years later.

33:44.556 --> 33:46.358 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

33:46.391 --> 33:49.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: We take a closer
look at the
power of these images with Anne
Barnard, "The

33:49.427 --> 33:53.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
New York Times" Beirut bureau
chief, and Susan
Moeller, she is a professor in
the Philip

33:53.765 --> 33:56.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Merrill College of Journalism at
the University
of Maryland.

33:56.268 --> 34:01.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's also author of "Compassion
Fatigue:
How the Media Sell Disease,
Famine, War and

34:01.172 --> 34:02.207 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Death."

34:02.240 --> 34:04.009 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Anne, I want to start with you.

34:04.042 --> 34:08.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Every day on social media, there
are more
graphic, more violent pictures
of little children

34:08.747 --> 34:10.081 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than this.

34:10.115 --> 34:11.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is it about this image of
the little
Omran that connected?

34:11.783 --> 34:17.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE BARNARD, THE NEW YORK
TIMES: Well, you
know, speaking for myself, I see
pictures

34:17.589 --> 34:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are literally gruesome
beyond belief,
that are hard to process
mentally, and they

34:24.596 --> 34:27.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are painful and compelling in
one way.

34:27.799 --> 34:34.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this picture resonated in
some ways because
it's easier to connect to, it's
a child in

34:34.706 --> 34:36.675 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
distress.

34:36.708 --> 34:42.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So many of the -- it's almost
ineffortable
to explain why but some of the
gestures he

34:42.113 --> 34:45.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
made could easily remind you of
a child you've
known.

34:45.216 --> 34:51.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of the -- you know, his
clothing, he
was wearing a shirt with a
Nickelodeon character

34:51.856 --> 34:53.658 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on it.

34:53.692 --> 35:00.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's like with Alan
Kurdi, who's body
was -- he was dead but his body
was intact

35:00.165 --> 35:05.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and it reminded people, you
know, of a child
sleeping on a beach.

35:05.537 --> 35:12.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think in a way that's more
shareable
in a social media age than a
really gruesome

35:12.544 --> 35:13.845 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
picture of death.

35:13.878 --> 35:17.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Susan, why did this
picture pop?

35:17.382 --> 35:19.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why did it get around the world
in 20 seconds?

35:19.484 --> 35:21.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUSAN MOELLER, INTERNATIONAL
CENTER FOR MEDIA
AND THE PUBLIC AGENDA: I think
one of the

35:21.619 --> 35:24.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reasons is because the child is
looking at
us.

35:24.756 --> 35:34.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But with a blank stare, where
often we see
on the news and we see in relief
aid agency

35:34.799 --> 35:39.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But with a blank stare, where
often we see
on the news and we see in relief
aid agency

35:39.971 --> 35:45.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
comment that, you know, help
this child, and
the child is looking at us, and
it almost

35:45.143 --> 35:47.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seems like the child is asking
us to do something.

35:47.512 --> 35:55.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Omran was also that same
pleading character.

35:55.520 --> 36:02.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: So, Anne, what
impacts do these
images have the potential to
yield?

36:02.560 --> 36:05.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARNARD: Well, you know, that's
a mixed bag.

36:05.964 --> 36:11.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can certainly think of
examples in history
like the famous picture of the
girl burned

36:11.269 --> 36:18.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by napalm by the U.S. military
in Vietnam,
that arguably changed public
opinion and maybe

36:18.443 --> 36:21.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
moved policy ultimately.

36:21.279 --> 36:28.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, on the other hand, many
images go
viral or touch people for a
moment and then

36:28.553 --> 36:30.388 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
people move on.

36:30.422 --> 36:37.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think, certainly, among
Syrians on all
sides of the conflict, there is
an increasing

36:37.195 --> 36:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mix of anger that comes up when
people express
sympathy about an image like
this because

36:41.766 --> 36:43.968 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it's, like, well, really?

36:44.002 --> 36:47.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You only just notice now that
this is happening
after five years?

36:47.539 --> 36:53.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it happened enough times
without anything
changing that people's
expectations are really

36:53.078 --> 36:54.813 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
low.

36:54.846 --> 36:59.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Susan, is it a
potential for
a government policy shift or
people moved

36:59.717 --> 37:01.586 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on a certain level?

37:01.619 --> 37:07.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOELLER: As Anne suggests that
normally government
policy doesn't shift with
images.

37:07.826 --> 37:12.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There may be rhetoric, there may
be a press
conference held, there maybe
sympathy expressed,

37:12.697 --> 37:15.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but you don't typically get
change.

37:15.366 --> 37:22.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What you do get is attention,
and with enough
attention, then you may get
reaction that

37:22.707 --> 37:24.075 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has an effect.

37:24.109 --> 37:26.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Anne, are people
motivated to
take action?

37:27.011 --> 37:32.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are there cases where it might
not be a government
policy shift but individuals
mobilize to such

37:32.917 --> 37:35.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
an extent that there is
impactful change?

37:35.453 --> 37:41.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARNARD: Well, I certainly have
had many people
ask me, how can I help people
like this?

37:41.559 --> 37:47.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What organizations are doing
work that can
help civilians caught in this
conflict?

37:47.932 --> 37:52.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other advocacy groups are
jumping on this
to say, well, this is -- enough
is enough,

37:52.670 --> 37:59.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's time to take more robust
action to stop
these air strikes by the
Russians and the

37:59.744 --> 38:01.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Syrian government.

38:01.146 --> 38:08.153 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Others are, you know, saying,
well, there
is not an easy answer.

38:08.186 --> 38:12.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some people don't find this a
reason to change
U.S. policy.

38:12.190 --> 38:14.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it depends on the person.

38:14.058 --> 38:20.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some reactions are political,
some are more
humanitarian, but I do think a
lot of people

38:20.698 --> 38:25.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
felt it like a punch in the gut,
even I did
after all this time covering the
conflict.

38:25.170 --> 38:28.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Susan, what are
people left to
do about it?

38:28.606 --> 38:30.041 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is writing a check the answer?

38:30.074 --> 38:33.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, there is a sense of
helplessness when
you see this image, too.

38:33.244 --> 38:39.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOELLER: Yes, I think Omran has
become, you
know, the current poster child
for Syria for

38:39.584 --> 38:46.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this moment in time, just like
Alan Kurdi
did a year ago, and we've had
other small

38:46.090 --> 38:48.393 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
children do in years' past.

38:48.426 --> 38:54.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think a poster child does
help us reach
into our wallets, reach into our
pockets,

38:55.033 --> 38:56.935 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and give.

38:56.968 --> 39:00.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I wrote a book called
"Compassion Fatigue",
and in that, I suggested that
one of the reasons

39:00.905 --> 39:06.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
why people sometimes say enough
is when they
feel helpless, is when they feel
like they

39:06.945 --> 39:08.846 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can't make a difference.

39:08.880 --> 39:16.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, being able to
figure out how
to make a difference can be
something that

39:16.721 --> 39:19.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a photograph like Omran can do.

39:19.591 --> 39:23.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In other words, identifying an
aid agency.

39:23.328 --> 39:31.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Alan Kurdi, for example, in the
24 hours after
that photograph appeared, just
one refugee

39:31.102 --> 39:35.006 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
agency received almost a quarter
million dollars.

39:35.039 --> 39:42.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we can say that help is
given that wouldn't
have been given otherwise.

39:42.480 --> 39:49.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Anne, is there a
correlation
between things that we can do at
home, say

39:49.053 --> 39:54.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a Confederate flag issue or an
LGBT issue
that people get fired up about
versus things

39:54.125 --> 40:00.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
overseas that might require the
action of
different governments and armies
and tanks

40:00.131 --> 40:01.899 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to move into places?

40:01.933 --> 40:09.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARNARD: Well, I do think people
find it a
bit opaque how they can affect
foreign policy,

40:09.207 --> 40:17.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
especially nowadays in the era
of just wars
that are going on behind the
scenes and with

40:17.115 --> 40:18.916 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
drones.

40:18.950 --> 40:23.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I do think, however, that,
you know, now
that there is a more active
protest movement

40:23.354 --> 40:26.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going on in the United States,
anything can
happen.

40:26.324 --> 40:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But again the issues are very
complex and
multi-sided.

40:29.927 --> 40:37.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, people remember that
the war in
Iraq was a huge failure and
they're wary of

40:37.302 --> 40:39.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Middle East in general, they
don't know
much about it.

40:39.837 --> 40:45.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
