41:49.006 --> 41:52.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN, PBS NEWSHOUR
ECONOMICS CORRESPONDENT:
Sam Polk was formerly a top dog
at one of

41:52.877 --> 41:54.612 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the world's top hedge funds.

41:54.645 --> 41:57.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAM POLK, SOCIAL ENTREPRENEUR:
My dad was
this sort of Willy Loman
character, this sort

41:57.849 --> 42:01.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of out-of-work salesman that
could never make
ends meet.

42:01.419 --> 42:08.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So when I was on Wall Street, my
entire life's
goal was to make more money than
the next

42:08.393 --> 42:10.161 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
guy.

42:10.194 --> 42:11.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DORCIA WHITE-BRAKE, GROCERYSHIP
GRADUATE:
Just going to pour a little bit
of salsa inside.

42:11.396 --> 42:12.697 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's like your own little bowl.

42:12.730 --> 42:14.132 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Wow, nice.

42:14.165 --> 42:17.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Dorcia White-Brake is a
teacher's
aid in Los Angeles.

42:17.835 --> 42:22.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Three kids, no car, the nearest
supermarket
miles away.

42:22.540 --> 42:27.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: So I can have, you
know, good
healthy food that tastes good.

42:27.378 --> 42:29.180 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have to take a bus and a
train.

42:29.213 --> 42:35.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: When I was 27, I had been
on Wall Street
for five or six years and I was
at this club

42:35.353 --> 42:42.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Las Vegas, and it was this
super-exclusive
club and there was $1,000
bottles of champagne,

42:42.226 --> 42:44.796 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and beautiful women all around.

42:44.829 --> 42:49.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My life finally looked like I'd
always wanted
it to look.

42:50.001 --> 42:51.469 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But I basically felt empty.

42:51.502 --> 42:55.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: So, basically, I
waited six months
for this application.

42:55.239 --> 42:56.974 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
SOLMAN: Really.

42:57.008 --> 43:00.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: Yes, and I got it
and I turned
it in and then it seemed like an
eternity.

43:00.678 --> 43:04.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I was waiting and waiting and
finally I got
a call.

43:04.248 --> 43:11.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: Got a call to join the
Los Angeles
non-profit Groceryships Program,
started by

43:11.122 --> 43:12.857 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Sam Polk.

43:12.890 --> 43:18.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: I started Groceryships
when I came to
understand that people are
living in food

43:18.930 --> 43:24.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
deserts, where there's very
little produce
for sale and tons and tons of
fast food.

43:24.335 --> 43:30.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: Groceryships is a
six-month scholarship
to buy healthy groceries, learn
to cook them,

43:30.975 --> 43:32.677 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and to share.

43:32.710 --> 43:36.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: And there's a box of
Kleenex in the
center because a lot of time is
devoted to

43:36.380 --> 43:43.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sharing about family, about body
issues, about
self-esteem and so, we have yet
to see a group

43:43.588 --> 43:47.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where you start talking about
those issues
and somebody doesn't burst into
tears.

43:47.492 --> 43:51.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: I need my box right
now, because,
I'm not kidding.

43:51.128 --> 43:52.096 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
SOLMAN: Really?

43:52.129 --> 43:53.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Just talking about it.

43:53.831 --> 43:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: Yes, because just
to be able
to tell people about my food
disorder.

43:58.769 --> 44:03.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I let so much out in that so
circle.

44:03.407 --> 44:07.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yeah, you know we went through a
lot of stuff
together.

44:07.078 --> 44:12.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whatever, whatever I was going
through, my
Groceryships family went through
it with me.

44:12.283 --> 44:18.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Groceryships is
expanding in L.A.,
but to Sam Polk it's only
prelude to his new

44:18.556 --> 44:20.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
venture, Everytable.

44:20.558 --> 44:25.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's just opened the first
outpost of what
he hopes will be a nationwide
chain of restaurants,

44:26.030 --> 44:31.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
dishing out healthy food,
furiously fast,
and challengingly cheap.

44:31.035 --> 44:35.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: So that means in
this s neighborhood,
which is south Los Angeles where
the per capita

44:35.139 --> 44:41.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
income is $13,000 a year, and
life expectancy
is ten years lower than more
affluent areas.

44:41.779 --> 44:43.514 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We price the meals at $4.

44:43.548 --> 44:45.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID FOSTER, CO-FOUNDER,
EVERYTABLE: Four
bucks is a great price here
compared to fast

44:45.750 --> 44:47.652 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
food, which is the predominant
option.

44:47.685 --> 44:53.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: David Foster also left a
rich career
in finance to join Sam Polk.

44:53.558 --> 44:59.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're about to open a second
Everytable
in upscale downtown L.A., $8 a
meal.

44:59.764 --> 45:03.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FOSTER: But eight bucks is also
a great price
compared to what's available in
the healthy

45:03.701 --> 45:05.269 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
fast casual space downtown.

45:05.303 --> 45:09.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: So, it's $8 versus $4
for exactly
the same food?

45:09.874 --> 45:11.208 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
POLK: That's right.

45:11.242 --> 45:14.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's basically making sure that
everyone can
afford healthy food.

45:14.445 --> 45:20.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: The same healthy food,
prepared in
the same central kitchen to keep
costs low,

45:20.251 --> 45:25.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, here's the key innovation,
sold at higher
prices in wealthier
neighborhoods to make

45:25.957 --> 45:28.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up for the super-skinny margins
in poor ones.

45:28.793 --> 45:36.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
POLK: In a world where
inequality is clearly
growing and becoming seen as
structural, we

45:36.267 --> 45:40.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think that this is the time for
a new business
that questions that fundamental
assumption

45:40.638 --> 45:42.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that prices should be the same
for everyone.

45:42.974 --> 45:46.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: This is one of the
dreams of all sellers,
right?

45:46.243 --> 45:48.079 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's price discrimination.

45:48.112 --> 45:54.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You want to charge people what's
they're actually
willing to pay, as opposed to
just have one

45:54.051 --> 45:55.753 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
price across the board.

45:55.786 --> 45:59.557 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FOSTER: We're not price
discriminating in
the sense of trying to make as
much money

45:59.590 --> 46:01.492 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
off of each customer as
possible.

46:01.525 --> 46:03.327 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're actually kind of doing the
opposite.

46:03.361 --> 46:07.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're saying we don't need to
make much if
any money on a lot of our
customers, because

46:07.732 --> 46:13.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what's driving us is not just
having a successful,
viable company, but more
importantly solving

46:13.571 --> 46:15.573 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this problem that afflicts a lot
of people.

46:15.606 --> 46:17.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Surprised that two guys
from Wall
Street are doing this?

46:17.908 --> 46:19.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DEBRA DIXON: Yes.

46:19.644 --> 46:24.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: Dedra Dixon's foundation
feeds the
homeless, getting leftovers from
Everytable

46:24.181 --> 46:25.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
just one day old.

46:26.017 --> 46:29.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIXON: There's not too many
places t around
in our community unfortunately
where you can

46:29.387 --> 46:31.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get salads, you can get these
meals.

46:31.422 --> 46:36.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, yes, that two guys from
Wall Street
can come down into south L.A.
and say there's

46:36.260 --> 46:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a need here that needs to be met
by way of
food and meet that need, I am
very surprised.

46:42.733 --> 46:44.502 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But grateful.

46:44.535 --> 46:49.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: Like other entrepreneurs
we've covered,
trying to bring good food to the
desert, in

46:49.974 --> 46:52.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Philadelphia, in Boston, Polk
sees the need
everywhere.

46:52.977 --> 46:58.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: Eventually, we'd like to
see an Everytable
store in every neighborhood in
the country.

46:58.115 --> 46:59.083 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Thousands?

46:59.116 --> 47:01.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
POLK: I would say tens of
thousands.

47:01.318 --> 47:05.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have over 50 investors,
including some
of the biggest venture capital
funds in the

47:05.956 --> 47:07.258 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

47:07.291 --> 47:10.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Including many of their
high-flying
former colleagues.

47:10.528 --> 47:16.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But despite the enthusiasm for
do-good ideas
like this, people aren't exactly
leaving Wall

47:16.300 --> 47:19.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Street in droves for more
meaningful careers.

47:19.437 --> 47:26.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: I think we all have inside
us both ambitions
which are things that we want
for ourself--

47:26.444 --> 47:29.346 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you know, money, power,
prestige.

47:29.380 --> 47:33.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we all have aspirations to
contribute
or make the world a better
place.

47:33.617 --> 47:38.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It just so happens that we live
in a culture
as a whole where ambitions are
celebrated

47:38.856 --> 47:42.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more than aspirations and it's
almost like
Wall Street is the most
distilled part of

47:42.993 --> 47:44.595 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that culture.

47:44.628 --> 47:48.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: And like any culture, it
reinforces
its norms in casual
conversation.

47:48.566 --> 47:50.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, what is your net
worth?

47:50.735 --> 47:52.136 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How many sticks have you made
this year?

47:52.169 --> 47:53.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
POLK: How many sticks?

47:53.404 --> 47:55.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: You call a million
dollars a stick
on Wall Street.

47:55.806 --> 48:01.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: So, you say: I'm up ten
sticks to say
I have ten million in profits
this year.

48:01.078 --> 48:06.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My bonus in my last year on Wall
Street was
more than my mom, a nurse
practitioner midwife

48:06.684 --> 48:08.519 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
had made for her entire life.

48:08.552 --> 48:10.454 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I was 30 years old.

48:10.488 --> 48:16.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: It had taken three years
after the
emptiness epiphany in the Vegas
nightclub,

48:16.093 --> 48:21.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but at 30, as he explained in
for "The Love
of Money", a "New York Times"
op-ed piece

48:21.265 --> 48:24.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that went viral and has now been
turned into
a book.

48:24.301 --> 48:30.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POLK: I came to understand that
even though
that billionaire siren song was
really attractive,

48:30.474 --> 48:35.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that in another way, that came
to seem like
a good way to waste your life.

48:35.146 --> 48:38.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You go to Wall Street and you
make all this
money and then you're 70 years
old and you're

48:38.649 --> 48:39.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on your deathbed and --

48:39.884 --> 48:42.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Hey, wait a second- -
not 70 on your
deathbed.

48:42.686 --> 48:45.022 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How about upping that number
just a bit?

48:45.055 --> 48:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
POLK: Ninety on your deathbed.

48:47.124 --> 48:52.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But at the end of the day, I
felt like I wanted
to be truly proud of what I'd
done with my

48:52.263 --> 48:53.230 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

48:53.264 --> 48:55.065 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: As for David Foster --

48:55.099 --> 48:58.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FOSTER: There are a lot of smart
people working
in finance, and I'd go as far as
to say that

48:58.502 --> 49:04.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are too many smart people
working in
finance and that thee value I
was adding versus

49:04.074 --> 49:07.178 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a replacement player was kind of
negligible.

49:07.211 --> 49:13.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I thought that there was
something out there
in the world, a bigger problem
that needed

49:13.217 --> 49:16.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
solving, beyond being another
person working
in the private equity industry.

49:16.954 --> 49:20.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Or another chef cooking
for the one
percent.

49:20.157 --> 49:22.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CRAIG HOPSON, EXECUTIVE CHIEF,
LE CIRQUE IN
NEW YORK: Hi, I'm Craig Hopson.

49:22.293 --> 49:24.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm executive chef here at Le
Cirque in New
York.

49:24.094 --> 49:26.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Hopson went from haute
cuisine to
Everytable.

49:26.964 --> 49:29.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOPSON: It could be thousands of
people a
day that buy the Everytable
meals.

49:30.000 --> 49:33.037 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I mean the audience is
unlimited.

49:33.070 --> 49:35.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Le Cirque, not so much.

49:35.406 --> 49:40.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: And Hopson too speaks in
sound bites
that would sound hokey if they
weren't so

49:40.110 --> 49:41.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
obviously earnest.

49:41.779 --> 49:46.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOPSON: It's great to be able to
be proud
of what I'm doing and be able to
give back

49:46.217 --> 49:49.987 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the people that really need
it and to make
a difference in the world.

49:50.020 --> 49:54.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: And speaking of hokey
lines, make
a difference they do.

49:54.325 --> 49:56.126 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WHITE-BRAKE: Bon appetit.

49:56.160 --> 50:01.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: This is economics
correspondent Paul
Solman, putting on the pounds,
healthfully,

50:01.699 --> 50:03.434 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in south Los Angeles.

50:03.467 --> 50:06.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's really nice.

50:06.303 --> 50:11.508 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
