50:11.542 --> 50:16.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Now to another of
our "Brief
But Spectacular" episodes.

50:16.614 --> 50:19.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from David
Remnick, editor
of "The New Yorker."

50:19.350 --> 50:21.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He describes how the magazine
has changed
over the years.

50:21.819 --> 50:23.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

50:23.687 --> 50:27.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID REMNICK, EDITOR, THE NEW
YORKER: I think
people's awareness has to begin
at some point,

50:27.625 --> 50:31.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some weird influence that gets
them going
that makes them enter the world.

50:31.128 --> 50:32.796 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For me, it was listening to Bob
Dylan.

50:32.830 --> 50:34.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I bought my first album.

50:34.565 --> 50:39.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was called "The Best of '66,"
and it had
a song called "I Want You" by
Bob Dylan.

50:39.270 --> 50:40.571 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was six years old.

50:40.604 --> 50:44.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I didn't know what he wanted
exactly but it
resonated with me.

50:44.341 --> 50:50.881 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You guys are fancy, I got to
tell you.

50:50.915 --> 50:56.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been the editor of "The
New Yorker"
magazine since 1998 and I've
been a writer

50:56.887 --> 50:58.789 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
here since 1992.

50:58.822 --> 51:05.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's changed from being the
editor of a weekly
print magazine to now a web
site, radio show,

51:05.729 --> 51:10.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a television show, floor wax,
dessert topping,
we're everything.

51:10.601 --> 51:16.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"The New Yorker Radio Hour" is a
program that's
both on terrestrial radio and a
podcast.

51:16.073 --> 51:21.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Now podcast and radio is
renaissance, just
as television is in many ways.

51:21.378 --> 51:26.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if "The New Yorker Radio
Hour" is in the
thick of that renaissance, I'm
very happy.

51:26.617 --> 51:29.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Editing is a really complicated
process.

51:29.553 --> 51:34.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Get the writer to do the best
form of the
writer's version of the piece.

51:34.258 --> 51:40.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
An editor who is obnoxious, in
my mind, is
the kind of editor that said
winkingly, that's

51:40.397 --> 51:41.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kind of my piece.

51:41.665 --> 51:44.034 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's just not what's done
here.

51:44.068 --> 51:50.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The greatest feeling of
satisfaction is to
run across somebody young who
has something

51:50.874 --> 51:56.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
new to say and saying it in a
different way
and help that person in some
subtle way get

51:56.613 --> 51:59.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be himself or herself, that
is thrilling.

51:59.049 --> 52:02.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Not everybody does everything at
the highest
level.

52:02.686 --> 52:07.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't expect an investigative
report to
necessarily be the next sense
and sensibility.

52:07.891 --> 52:11.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What you want is to be accurate
and deep and
clear.

52:11.528 --> 52:15.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My editor up in New York, when I
write, the
rare times that I write is a guy
named Henry

52:15.132 --> 52:16.867 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Fender (ph).

52:16.900 --> 52:22.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He might say something like this
-- very good
things here -- and if that
happens, I know

52:22.606 --> 52:24.975 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we're in for a long ride.

52:25.009 --> 52:27.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Everybody does his or her job in
a moment
in time.

52:27.845 --> 52:33.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My moment in time is not only to
make the
magazine as great as it possibly
can be but

52:33.851 --> 52:39.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
help us cross this technological
and even
financial roaring river of
change.

52:39.723 --> 52:44.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Internet is at the center of
everybody's
attention and how we come into
people's households

52:44.995 --> 52:51.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or palms or field division has
changed radically
and I have to leave a "New
Yorker" that's

52:51.602 --> 52:56.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
got its soul as well as its
technological
act together.

52:56.407 --> 53:01.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm David Remnick and this is my
"Brief but
Spectacular" view of "The New
Yorker."

